{"title_page": "Leonard Fournette", "text_new": "{{short description|American football running back}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n| name                = Leonard Fournette\n| image               = Leonard Fournette 2.png\n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Fournette in 2019\n| current_team        = Philadelphia Eagles  \n| number              = \n| position            = [[Running back]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1995|1|18}}\n| birth_place         = [[New Orleans, Louisiana]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 0\n| weight_lbs          = 228\n| high_school         = [[St. Augustine High School (New Orleans)|St. Augustine]]<br/>([[New Orleans|New Orleans, Louisiana]])\n| college             = [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]]\n| draftyear           = 2017\n| draftround          = 1\n| draftpick           = 4\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] ({{NFL Year|2017}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Active\n| highlights          = \n* Consensus [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2015 College Football All-America Team|2015]])\n* First-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] ([[2015 All-SEC football team|2015]])\n* Second-team All-SEC ([[2016 All-SEC football team|2016]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[USA Today All-USA high school football team|''USA Today'' High School All-American]] ([[2012 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2012]], [[2013 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2013]])\n| statleague = NFL\n| statweek   = \n| statseason = 2019\n| statlabel1   = [[Rushing yards]]\n| statvalue1   = 2,631\n| statlabel2   = [[Average|Rushing average]]\n| statvalue2   = 4.0\n| statlabel3   = [[Touchdown|Rushing touchdowns]]\n| statvalue3   = 17\n| statlabel4   = [[Reception (American football)|Receptions]]\n| statvalue4   = 134\n| statlabel5   = [[Receiving yards]] \n| statvalue5   = 1,009\n| statlabel6   = [[Touchdown|Receiving touchdowns]]\n| statvalue6   = 2\n| nflnew              = leonardfournette/2557973\n}}\n\n'''Leonard Joseph Fournette III''' (born January 18, 1995) is an [[American football]] [[running back]] for the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]], and was drafted by the Jaguars with the fourth overall pick in the [[2017 NFL Draft]]. Fournette was a consensus [[College Football All-America Team|All-America]] selection following his sophomore season in 2015, after setting school single-season records with 1,953 rushing yards and 22 rushing touchdowns, and leading the country with 162.8 rushing yards per game. Various experts regarded him as the best player in college football, comparing him to all-time great [[Herschel Walker]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Roser |first=Jerit |url=http://www.nola.com/lsu/index.ssf/2015/09/leonard_fournette_herschel_wal.html |title=Herschel Walker: Leonard Fournette 'is better than I was' |date=September 30, 2015 |work=The Times-Picayune |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Maisel |first=Ivan |url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/13817380/lsu-leonard-fournette-lebron-best-kind-different |title=Leonard Fournette: The best kind of different |date=October 7, 2015 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFournette joined the Tigers with near-unprecedented hype in 2014 after an outstanding career at [[St. Augustine High School (New Orleans)|St. Augustine High School]] in [[New Orleans]], winning the [[USA Today High School Football Offensive Player of the Year|2013 ''USA Today'' High School Football Offensive Player of the Year]] and being named the No. 1 overall recruit in 2014 senior class according to [[ESPN]], ''[[247Sports.com]]'', and [[CBS Sports]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Yellin |first=Lyons |url=http://www.nola.com/recruiting/index.ssf/2013/04/st_augustines_leonard_fournett.html |title=ESPN names St. Augustine's Leonard Fournette nation's No. 1 recruit |date=April 18, 2013 |work=The Times-Picayune |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> Fournette's brother, Lanard, is a former [[running back]] at [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]].\n\n==Early years==\nRaised in the [[7th Ward of New Orleans]], Fournette grew up in a troubled area that was often affected by violence and gang activity, especially after [[Hurricane Katrina]] hit in 2005. Fournette credited Katrina as kick-starting his football career after he moved to Houston and back within a year because of the hurricane evacuation. When he came back to New Orleans he played [[high school football|football]] at [[St. Augustine High School (New Orleans)|St. Augustine High School]], and competed in track and field.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Boudwin |first=Julie |url=http://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2017/01/leonard_fournette_gives_back_t_1.html |title=Leonard Fournette gives back to St. Augustine on his 22nd birthday |work=NOLA.com |access-date=February 3, 2018 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204123925/https://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2017/01/leonard_fournette_gives_back_t_1.html |archive-date=February 4, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> His [[200 metres]] regional mark of 21.57 seconds is fastest in 4A, and his 10.68 in the [[100 metres]] is only .02 off the best time. He also competed in the [[4 \u00d7 100 metres relay]] and [[4 \u00d7 200 metres relay]]. On the varsity football team, he was a starter since his freshman year and compiled 7,619 rushing yards and 88 rushing touchdowns for his career.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/jacksonville-jaguars/post/_/id/25487 |title=Jaguars star Leonard Fournette forges bond with state champs |last=DiRocco |first=Michael |date=May 31, 2018 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2019}}</ref> He rushed for more than 2,500 yards and 30 touchdowns his freshman season, and became the first-ever freshman to earn a scholarship offer from [[LSU Tigers football|Louisiana State]].<ref name=\"ESPN_Scarborough\">{{Cite news |last=Scarborough |first=Alex |url=http://espn.go.com/colleges/alabama/story/_/id/8090719/2014-running-back-leonard-fournette-overcome-adversity-excel-life |title=2014 running back Leonard Fournette has overcome adversity to excel in life |date=June 25, 2012 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> His sophomore year ended with 1,900 yards rushing and 27 touchdowns. As a junior, he registered 2,135 rushing yards and 31 touchdowns and was an LFCA Class 4A First-Team All-State honoree. In his senior year, Fournette ran for 1,792 yards and 16 touchdowns and added 45 receptions for 745 yards and six scores. Early in the season, he had a heralded performance with two touchdowns and 262 yards rushing against [[Malachi Dupre]]'s [[John Curtis Christian High School|John Curtis Christian]], which was nationally televised by [[ESPN2]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hamilton |first=Gerry |url=http://insider.espn.go.com/college-sports/recruiting/football/story/_/id/9791414/week-was-in-football-recruiting |title=Fournette breaks out: Nation's top recruit Leonard Fournette puts on a show on ESPN2 |date=October 8, 2013 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref> St. Augustine ended the season with a 9\u20132 record and an appearance in the [[Louisiana High School Athletic Association|LHSAA]] Division I semifinal game, where they were upset 31\u201328 by [[Archbishop Rummel High School]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Derry |first=Jim |url=http://highschoolsports.nola.com/news/article/5650481414329799202/fifth-seeded-rummel-shocks-st-augustine-31-28/ |title=Fifth-seeded Rummel shocks St. Augustine, 31\u201328 |date=December 1, 2013 |work=The Times-Picayune |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> Fournette was named [[Mr. Football Award (Louisiana)|Louisiana's 2013 Mr. Football]] by the Louisiana Sports Writers Association, and also was selected as an All-American by ''[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]'' and ''[[USA Today]]'', as well as ''USA Today'' Offensive Player of the Year, the first from Louisiana since [[Ryan Perrilloux]] in 2004. After the season, Fournette participated in the [[Under Armour All-America Game]] where he caught a 36-yard touchdown pass and rushed for 43 yards on nine carries.\n\nUnanimously regarded as the best running back prospect of his class, Fournette was one of the most highly recruited players ever to come out of Louisiana. [[ESPN]] ranked him as the No. 1 recruit in the class of 2014,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/football/recruiting/playerrankings/_/class/2014/order/true |title=2014 ESPN 300 |website=ESPN.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821174952/http://www.espn.com/college-sports/football/recruiting/playerrankings/_/class/2014/order/true |archive-date=August 21, 2016 |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> as did [[Scout.com]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.scout.com/topic/players?s=73&category=Football%20Recruiting&league=HS&classYear=2014 |title=2014 High School Recruits Ranking |website=Scout.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151008014041/https://scout.com/topic/players/?s=73&category=Football%20Recruiting&league=HS&classYear=2014 |archive-date=October 8, 2015 |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> At the 2014 Under Armour All-America Game, Fournette announced his decision to attend [[LSU Tigers football|Louisiana State University]] (LSU).<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tyson |first=Derek |url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/recruiting/football/story/_/id/10232850/top-recruits-make-commitments-armour-all-america-game |title=Leonard Fournette commits to LSU |date=January 3, 2014 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nFournette attended and played college football for LSU from 2014\u20132016 under head coaches [[Les Miles]] and [[Ed Orgeron]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/leonard-fournette-1.html |title=Leonard Fournette College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Freshman season===\nFournette's college career was preceded by very high expectations and hype, and he was often called \"the next [[Adrian Peterson]]\".<ref name=\"cbssports.com\">{{Cite news |last=Fornelli |first=Tom |url=http://www.cbssports.com/collegefootball/eye-on-college-football/24693042/les-miles-wants-to-temper-the-fournette-hype-he-helped-create |title=Les Miles wants to temper the Fournette hype he helped create |date=September 3, 2014 |work=CBSSports.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"nola.com\">{{Cite news |last=Duncan |first=Jeff |url=http://www.nola.com/lsu/index.ssf/2014/08/hold_the_heisman_leonard_fourn.html |title=Leonard Fournette's collegiate debut is more fizzle than sizzle |date=August 31, 2014 |work=The Times-Picayune |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> In his collegiate debut against the [[2014 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin Badgers]] on August 30, 2014, Fournette ran for 18 yards on eight carries.<ref name=\"nola.com\" /> After the game, LSU head coach Les Miles downplayed the Fournette hype. \"First games are not to be comparable to his 30th game,\" said Miles. \"Expectations are unrealistic.\"<ref name=\"cbssports.com\" />\nIn his second game, against the [[2014 Sam Houston State Bearkats football team|Sam Houston State Bearkats]], Fournette rushed for 92 yards on 13 attempts and scored his first collegiate rushing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-09-06-louisiana-state.html |title=Sam Houston State at Louisiana State Box Score, September 6, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> In the fifth week of the season, the [[2014 New Mexico State Aggies football team|New Mexico State Aggies]] traveled to [[Tiger Stadium (LSU)|Death Valley]] to face the #17 LSU Tigers, and Fournette ran for 122 yards on 18 carries and scored two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-09-27-louisiana-state.html |title=New Mexico State at Louisiana State Box Score, September 27, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> This effort put Fournette at the top of the Tigers' rushing list for the season.<ref name=\"m.espn.go.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://m.espn.com/ncf/playergamelog?playerId=559752&season=2014&wjb |title=Leonard Fournette 2014 Game Log |website=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> On October 11 against SEC [[Florida\u2013LSU football rivalry|rival]] [[2014 Florida Gators football team|Florida]], Fournette rushed the ball 27 times for 140 yards and two touchdowns to help LSU secure a 30\u201327 last-second win in [[Ben Hill Griffin Stadium|The Swamp]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-10-11-florida.html |title=LSU at Florida Box Score, October 11, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> Against undefeated and #3 [[2014 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]], who led the nation in stopping the run, Fournette shook off an early goal line fumble and rushed 23 times for 113 yards to go along with two receptions for 41 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-10-25-louisiana-state.html |title=Ole Miss at Louisiana State Box Score, October 25, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> LSU ran the ball 12 times for 92 yards on a 13-play, 95-yard touchdown drive to upset the Rebels by a score of 10\u20137 in Death Valley.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Martel |first=Brett |url=http://www.cbssports.com/collegefootball/gametracker/recap/NCAAF_20141025_MISS@LSU/no-24-lsu-upends-no3-mississippi-10-7 |title=No. 24 LSU upends No.3 Mississippi, 10\u20137 |date=October 26, 2014 |work=CBSSports.com |access-date=December 12, 2016 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Fournette finished the season against [[2014 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]] in the [[2014 Music City Bowl]] with 11 carries for 143 yards and two touchdowns. In addition, he had a 100-yard kickoff return for a touchdown in the loss to the Fighting Irish.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sparks |first=Adam |url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/college/2014/12/30/lsu-leonard-fournette-sizzles-music-city-bowl-loss-notre-dame/21084229/ |title=LSU's Leonard Fournette sizzles in Music City Bowl |date=December 30, 2014 |work=The Tennessean |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-12-30-louisiana-state.html |title=Music City Bowl \u2013 Notre Dame vs Louisiana State Box Score, December 30, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Sophomore season===\n\nFournette started his sophomore season with a strong performance of 159 rushing yards and three touchdowns against [[2015 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team|Mississippi State]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-09-12-mississippi-state.html |title=LSU at Mississippi State Box Score, September 12, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, a victory over [[2015 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]], he finished with 228 rushing yards and three touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-09-19-louisiana-state.html |title=Auburn at Louisiana State Box Score, September 19, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> He rushed for a career-high 244 yards and two touchdowns against [[2015 Syracuse Orange football team|Syracuse]] in the [[Carrier Dome]], six yards shy of tying [[Alley Broussard]]'s school record of 250 yards against [[2004 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]] in 2004.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Moormann |first=Dave |url=http://www.dailycomet.com/article/20041122/SPORTS/411220315 |title=LSU's ground attack overcomes sluggish passing game |date=November 22, 2004 |work=The Daily Comet |access-date=December 12, 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928045308/http://www.dailycomet.com/article/20041122/SPORTS/411220315 |archive-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref> Fournette had an 87-yard touchdown run nullified by an [[illegal formation]] call late in the game.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=400603849 |title=Leonard Fournette first LSU RB to run for 200 yards in consecutive games |date=September 26, 2015 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> The following week, against [[2015 Eastern Michigan Eagles football team|Eastern Michigan]], Fournette rushed for 233 yards, becoming the first player in [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC) history to rush for 200 or more yards in three straight games.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/statsinfo/post/_/id/110157/lsus-fournette-on-an-unprecedented-run |title=LSU's Leonard Fournette on an unprecedented run |date=October 6, 2015 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> Against [[2015 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team|Western Kentucky]], Fournette ran for 150 yards, his ninth consecutive 100+ yards rushing game, a streak that dated back to the [[2014 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]] game in late November 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-10-24-louisiana-state.html |title=Western Kentucky at Louisiana State Box Score, October 24, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> He tied a school record originally established by [[Charles Alexander (running back)|Charles Alexander]] in [[1978 LSU Tigers football team|1978]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.seccountry.com/louisiana-state/lsu-running-back-leonard-fournette-matches-school-record-consecutive-100-yard-rushing-games |title=LSU running back Leonard Fournette matches school record consecutive 100-yard rushing games |last=Harris |first=Terrance |date=October 24, 2015 |website=SEC Country |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> Fournette's streak ended the next game against [[Alabama\u2013LSU football rivalry|rival]] [[2015 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]], the nation's best rushing defense, at [[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]]. He was held to 31 yards on 19 attempts, as the Crimson Tide handed LSU its first loss of the season.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/recap?id=400603905 |title=Derrick Henry (210 yards, 3 TDs) rolls as Bama contains Leonard Fournette, LSU |date=November 8, 2015 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=April 3, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In the [[2015 Texas Bowl]], Fournette ran for 212 yards and scored five total touchdowns as the Tigers defeated [[2015 Texas Tech Red Raiders football team|Texas Tech]], 56\u201327.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nola.com/lsu/index.ssf/2015/12/lsu_leonard_fournette_trample.html |title=LSU, Leonard Fournette trample Texas Tech in Texas Bowl, 56\u201327 |last=Kleinpeter |first=Jim |date=December 29, 2015 |website=The Times-Picayune |access-date=January 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn his sophomore season, Fournette set school records with 1,953 rushing yards and 22 rushing touchdowns. With an average of 162.8 rushing yards per game, he won the NCAA rushing title, awarded to the player with the highest rushing yards per game average each season.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kleinpeter |first=Jim |url=http://www.nola.com/lsu/index.ssf/2016/01/leonard_fournette_wins_ncaa_ru.html |title=Leonard Fournette wins NCAA rushing title |date=January 12, 2016 |work=The Times-Picayune |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> He finished sixth in [[Heisman Trophy]] voting, earning 110 points. He earned consensus [[College Football All-America Team|All-America]] honors as he was named to the first team by three official selectors: the [[Associated Press]] (AP),<ref>{{Cite news |last=Russo |first=Ralph D. |url=http://collegefootball.ap.org/article/heisman-trophy-winner-henry-highlights-ap-all-america-team |title=Heisman Trophy Winner Henry Highlights AP All-America Team |date=December 13, 2015 |access-date=December 12, 2016 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> the [[Walter Camp Football Foundation]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Carbone |first=Al |url=http://waltercamp.org/126th-walter-camp-all-america-teams-announced/ |title=126th Walter Camp All-America Teams |date=December 10, 2015 |access-date=December 12, 2016 |publisher=Walter Camp Football Foundation}}</ref> and the [[Football Writers Association of America]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sportswriters.net/fwaa/news/2015/allamerica151214.html |title=2015 AutoNation FWAA All-America Team Unveiled |date=December 14, 2015 |access-date=December 12, 2016 |publisher=Football Writers Association of America}}</ref> SEC coaches,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kalland |first=Robby |url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/2015-coaches-all-sec-team-alabama-leads-the-way-with-10-selections/ |title=2015 Coaches' All-SEC Team: Alabama leads the way with 10 selections |date=December 8, 2015 |access-date=December 12, 2016 |publisher=CBS Sports}}</ref> the [[Associated Press]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://collegefootball.ap.org/article/2015-associated-press-all-sec-football-team |title=2015 Associated Press All-SEC football team |date=December 14, 2015 |access-date=December 12, 2016 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> and ESPN.com<ref>{{Cite news |last=Aschoff |first=Edward |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/sec/post/_/id/111828/the-espn-com-2015-all-sec-team |title=2015 ESPN.com All-SEC team: Derrick Henry, Leonard Fournette lead the way |date=December 9, 2015 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> each named Fournette to their All-SEC first team.\n\n===Junior season===\nEntering his junior season, Fournette was expected to contend for the [[Heisman Trophy]], and was one of the preseason favorites to win the award.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Chiusano |first=Anthony |url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/football/hand-him/2016-08-28/heisman-watch-early-favorites-take-home-trophy-2016 |title=Heisman Watch: Early favorites to take home the trophy in 2016 |date=August 29, 2016 |work=NCAA.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Ellis |first=Zach |url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2015/12/14/heisman-trophy-2016-race-way-too-early |title=Heisman Watch: A way-too-early look at the 2016 Heisman race |date=December 14, 2015 |work=Sports Illustrated |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> During a scrimmage game prior to the [[2016 LSU Tigers football team|2016 season]], Fournette sustained a [[high ankle sprain]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Dellenger |first=Ross |url=http://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_e9e4ff42-7f46-11e6-930a-1b2392133476.html |title=Details of Leonard Fournette's ankle injury? ESPN's Dr. Jerry Punch explains... |date=September 20, 2016 |work=The Advocate |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Patterson |first=Chip |url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/lsus-worst-nightmare-leonard-fournette-in-boot-following-ankle-injury/ |title=Scary scenario for LSU: Leonard Fournette in boot following ankle injury |date=August 16, 2016 |access-date=December 12, 2016 |publisher=CBS Sports}}</ref> but was well enough to return for the season opener against [[2016 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]] at [[Lambeau Field]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2016-09-03-wisconsin.html |title=LSU vs Wisconsin Box Score, September 3, 2016 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> Late in the game against Wisconsin, he bruised the same ankle and missed the next week's game against [[2016 Jacksonville State Gamecocks football team|Jacksonville State]] as a result. He re-injured it against SEC West rival [[2016 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] on September 24 in a 101-yard rushing effort, causing him to miss the next two games.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Dellenger |first=Ross |url=http://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_31a03b84-89bb-11e6-a094-eb0773fc5e84.html |title=LSU Practice Report: Still no Leonard Fournette, offensive line rotation and more |date=October 3, 2016 |work=The Advocate |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> On October 22, his first game back, Fournette rushed for 284 yards and three touchdowns against [[2016 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]] to set a new single-game school record for rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ching |first=David |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/sec/post/_/id/122721/welcome-back-leonard-fournette-smashes-lsu-rushing-record-in-return |title=Welcome back, Leonard: Fournette smashes LSU rushing record in return |date=October 22, 2016 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> His school record was surpassed later in the season by [[Derrius Guice]] by one yard. With his ankle still not fully healed, Fournette was not expected to play against [[2016 Florida Gators football team|Florida]] on November 19, and did not suit up for pregame warm-ups. However, after a pregame scuffle between the teams in which Fournette shoved a Florida assistant coach,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Curtis |first=Charles |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ftw/2016/11/19/lsus-leonard-fournette-florida-assistant-coach-appear-to-be-involved-in-pregame-skirmish/94126590/ |title=LSU's Leonard Fournette, Florida assistant coach part of pregame skirmish |date=November 19, 2016 |work=USA Today |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> LSU head coach [[Ed Orgeron]] granted him permission to play. Still visibly bothered by the injury, he managed only 40 yards on 12 carries and did not play in the fourth quarter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2016-11-19-louisiana-state.html |title=Florida at Louisiana State Box Score, November 19, 2016 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> Due to the injury, he did not travel with the team to [[College Station, Texas|College Station]] to face [[2016 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]] in the final game of the regular season.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Dellenger |first=Ross |url=http://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_7bf7d420-b1b2-11e6-851e-f7b6064f27ef.html |title=Source: LSU's Leonard Fournette did not make trip, won't play vs. Texas A&M on Thanksgiving |date=November 23, 2016 |work=The Advocate |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> He finished his junior season having carried 129 times for 843 yards and eight touchdowns in seven games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/leonard-fournette-1/gamelog/2016/ |title=Leonard Fournette 2016 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn December 5, 2016, Fournette announced his intention to enter the [[2017 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Goodbread |first=Chase |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000751840/article/leonard-fournette-intends-to-enter-2017-nfl-draft |title=Leonard Fournette intends to enter 2017 NFL Draft |date=December 5, 2016 |work=NFL.com |access-date=December 5, 2015}}</ref> To avoid injury, his coach told him to skip the [[2016 Citrus Bowl (December)|2016 Citrus Bowl]], which LSU won over [[2016 Louisville Cardinals football team|Louisville]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ching |first=David |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/18293243/leonard-fournette-lsu-tigers-play-buffalo-wild-wings-citrus-bowl |title=Leonard Fournette won't play Buffalo Wild Wings Citrus Bowl |date=December 16, 2016 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 16, 2016}}</ref> Fournette finished his college career having rushed for 3,830 yards, the fourth-most by a player in LSU history behind [[Charles Alexander (running back)|Charles Alexander]], [[Dalton Hilliard]], and [[Kevin Faulk]]. His 40 rushing touchdowns are tied for third most in school history with Alexander and behind Hilliard and Faulk.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/louisiana-state/rushing.html |title=LSU Fighting Tigers Rushing |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=4 style=\"text-align: center; font-weight:bold; background-color:#FDD023; color:#461D7C;\"| Leonard Fournette !!colspan=5| Rushing !!colspan=3|Receiving\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! GP !! GS !! Att !! Yards !! Avg !! Long !! TDs !! Rec !! Yards !! TDs\n|-\n| [[2014 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2014]] || [[2014 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]] || 13 || 6 || 187 || 1,034 || 5.5 || 89 || 10 || 7 || 127 || 0\n|-\n| [[2015 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2015]] || [[2015 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]] || 11 || 11 || 271 || 1,953 || 6.4 || 87 || 22 || 18 || 209 || 1\n|-\n| [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2016]] || [[2016 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]] || 7 || 7 || 129 || 843 || 6.5 || 78 || 8 || 15 || 146 || 0\n|- style=\"background:#555; font-weight:bold; color:white;\"\n| colspan=2 | College Totals || 31 || 24 || 616 || 3,830 || 6.2 || 89 || 40 || 40 || 482 || 1\n|}\n\n''Source:''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/leonard-fournette-1.html |title=Leonard Fournette College Stats |website=Sports-Reference.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nComing out of college, Fournette was highly touted as a top ten pick in the upcoming draft and was ranked as the third best prospect going into the NFL Combine. He arrived at the NFL combine weighing in five pounds heavier than his playing weight in college and opted to only participate in the vertical and 40-yard dash. At LSU's Pro Day, he opted to only partake in positional drills. He was ranked the top overall running back prospect by NFLDraftScout.com, and second behind [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State's]] [[Dalvin Cook]] by [[Pro Football Focus]] and ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=130694&draftyear=2017&genpos=RB |title=*Leonard Fournette, DS #1 RB, LSU |website=nfldraftscout.com |access-date=May 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.profootballfocus.com/draft-college-football-top-32-prospects-for-2017-nfl-draft/ |title=Top 32 Prospects for the 2017 NFL Draft |date=November 30, 2016 |website=profootballfocus.com |access-date=May 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/2017-nfl-draft-position-rankings |title=2017 NFL draft rankings: Top prospects by position |last=Burke |first=Chris |date=April 24, 2017 |website=si.com |access-date=May 10, 2017}}</ref>\n{{external media\n| video1 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/0ap3000000796763/Leonard-Fournette-2017-Combine-Workout Fournette's NFL Combine workout]\n| video2 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/0ap3000000789630/Leonard-Fournette-runs-official-4-51-40-yard-dash Leonard Fournette's 40-yard dash]\n| video3 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/0ap3000000797912/Leonard-Fournette-s-Pro-Day-highlights Fournette's Pro Day highlights]\n}}\n\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 0\u00bd\n|       weight = 240\n|         dash = 4.51\n|    ten split = 1.59\n| twenty split = 2.65\n|      shuttle = \n|   cone drill = \n|     vertical = 28\u00bd\n|     broad ft = \n|     broad in = \n|        bench = \n|    wonderlic = \n|     arm span = {{frac|31|5|8}}\n|    hand span = {{frac|9|1|4}}\n|         note = All values from [[NFL Combine]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/leonard-fournette?id=2557973 |title=Combine Player Profiles - Leonard Fournette |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.draftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=130694&draftyear=2017&genpos=rb |title=*Leonard Fournette -\u00a0LSU,\u00a0RB\u00a0:\u00a02017 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile |website=Draft Scout |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920200114/http://www.draftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=130694&draftyear=2017&genpos=rb |archive-date=September 20, 2018 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/0ap3000000796763/Leonard-Fournette-2017-Combine-Workout |title=Leonard Fournette 2017 Combine Workout |website=www.nfl.com |access-date=August 20, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{external media\n| video1 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/0ap3000000803362/Jaguars-select-Leonard-Fournette-No-4-in-the-2017-NFL-Draft Jaguars select Fournette fourth overall]\n| video2 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/0ap3000000803150/Leonard-Fournette-arrives-at-the-NFL-Draft-with-his-parents Fournette arrives at 2017 NFL Draft]\n}}\nThe [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] selected Fournette fourth overall in the [[2017 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000803317/article/jaguars-select-rb-leonard-fournette-with-fourth-pick |title=Jaguars select RB Leonard Fournette with fourth pick |last=Orr |first=Conor |date=April 27, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref> He was the first running back taken in that year's draft.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2017/draft.htm |title=2017 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> On May 17, 2017, the Jacksonville Jaguars signed Fournette to a four-year, $27 million contract with a $18 million signing bonus.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000809518/article/leonard-fournette-signs-rookie-deal-with-jaguars |title=Leonard Fournette signs rookie deal with Jaguars |last=Patra |first=Kevin |website=NFL.com |access-date=May 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n\n===2017 season===\nFournette made his regular season debut on September 10, 2017, against the [[2017 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]] at [[NRG Stadium]]. He rushed for 100 yards and a touchdown on 26 carries as the Jaguars won 29\u20137.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/redskins/fournette-strong-defense-lead-jaguars-over-texans-29-7/2017/09/10/e47f2fcc-9666-11e7-af6a-6555caaeb8dc_story.html |title=Fournette, strong defense lead Jaguars over Texans 29\u20137 |last=Rieken |first=Kristie |website=[[The Washington Post]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914180127/https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/redskins/fournette-strong-defense-lead-jaguars-over-texans-29-7/2017/09/10/e47f2fcc-9666-11e7-af6a-6555caaeb8dc_story.html |archive-date=September 14, 2017 |access-date=September 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709100htx.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Houston Texans \u2013 September 10th, 2017 |website=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]] |access-date=September 14, 2017}}</ref> In Week 4, against the [[2017 New York Jets season|New York Jets]], Fournette recorded a 10-yard reception in the first quarter for his first career receiving touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201710010nyj.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at New York Jets \u2013 October 1st, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 5, 2017}}</ref> In Week 5 against the [[2017 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], Fournette posted an impressive performance with 181 rushing yards, including a Jaguars franchise-record 90-yard run in the fourth quarter, and two touchdowns as the Jaguars won 30\u20139.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Graves |first=Will |url=http://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/article_12a234e6-ac68-11e7-ad18-b3c9625a3132.html |title=Leonard Fournette's 181 yards, 2 touchdowns cap off Jaguars' defense-fueled 31\u20139 win over Steelers |date=October 8, 2017 |work=The Advocate |access-date=October 8, 2017 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 6 against the [[2017 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]], Fournette carried 21 times for 130 yards, including a 75-yard touchdown run on the Jaguars' first play from scrimmage. He left the game in the fourth quarter with a minor ankle injury as the Jaguars lost to the Rams, 27\u201317.<ref>{{Cite news |last=DiRocco |first=Michael |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/21036865/jacksonville-jaguars-rb-leonard-fournette-sprains-ankle-loss-los-angeles-rams |title=Leonard Fournette sprains ankle |date=October 15, 2017 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=October 15, 2017}}</ref> Because of the ankle injury, he was ruled out for Week 7. Following a bye week, more trouble arose as Fournette was declared inactive for Week 9 against the [[2017 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]] as he violated team rules.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000871746/article/leonard-fournette-out-for-jaguars-after-rule-violation |title=Leonard Fournette out for Jaguars after rule violation |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=November 5, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=November 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 13 games and starts, Fournette finished his rookie year with 1,040 rushing yards and nine rushing touchdowns along with 302 receiving yards and a receiving touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/F/FourLe00/gamelog/2017/ |title=Leonard Fournette 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> He was ranked 58th by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2018]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2018/0ap3000000933651/Top-100-Players-of-2018-Leonard-Fournette-No-58 |title='Top 100 Players of 2018': Jacksonville Jaguars running back Leonard Fournette |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Jaguars finished the 2017 season with a 10\u20136 record, clinching the [[AFC South]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/jax/2017.htm |title=2017 Jacksonville Jaguars Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2017\u201318_NFL_playoffs#AFC:_Jacksonville_Jaguars_10,_Buffalo_Bills_3|Wild Card Round]] against the [[2017 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], Fournette struggled, rushing for 57 yards on 21 carries as the Jaguars won 10\u20133.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801070jax.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Buffalo Bills at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 January 7th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2017\u201318_NFL_playoffs#AFC:_Jacksonville_Jaguars_45,_Pittsburgh_Steelers_42|Divisional Round]] against the [[2017 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], he briefly left the game with an ankle injury, but returned and finished with 109 yards and three touchdowns as the Jaguars won 45\u201342.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.duluthnewstribune.com/sports/4388008-jaguars-withstand-late-rally-topple-steelers-45-42 |title=Jaguars withstand late rally, topple Steelers 45-42 |date=January 14, 2018 |website=[[Duluth News Tribune]] |language=en |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref> The following week, in the [[2017\u201318_NFL_playoffs#AFC_Championship_Game:_New_England_Patriots_24,_Jacksonville_Jaguars_20|AFC Championship]] against the [[2017 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], Fournette ran for 76 yards and a touchdown, but the Jaguars lost 24\u201320.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801210nwe.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 Jacksonville Jaguars at New England Patriots \u2013 January 21st, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018 season===\nFournette injured his hamstring during the season-opening 20-15 victory against the [[2018 New York Giants season|New York Giants]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24625351 |title=Jags RB Fournette out with hamstring injury |last=DiRocco |first=Mike |date=September 9, 2018 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2019}}</ref> He missed the next two games before returning against the [[2018 New York Jets season|New York Jets]], where he aggravated the injury and was ruled out indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/leonard-fournette-out-indefinitely-after-re-aggravating-hamstring-injury-sunday/ |title=Leonard Fournette out indefinitely after aggravating hamstring injury Sunday |last=Dubin |first=Jared |date=October 1, 2018 |website=CBSSports.com |access-date=November 26, 2018}}</ref> After missing four more games, he returned against the division rival [[2018 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], rushing for 53 yards and a touchdown with 56 receiving yards and a receiving touchdown as the Jaguars narrowly lost 29\u201326.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201811110clt.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Indianapolis Colts - November 11th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=September 20, 2019}}</ref> Against the [[2018 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], Fournette had his best game of the season, rushing for 95 yards and two touchdowns. However, after a [[Donte Moncrief]] reception that was initially ruled a touchdown in the third quarter, Fournette got into a fistfight with Bills defender [[Shaq Lawson]] as part of a brawl that broke out between the Jaguars and Bills, and the two were subsequently ejected from the game. Without Fournette, the Jaguars lost 24\u201321.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2807726-leonard-fournette-shaq-lawson-ejected-after-brawl-in-jaguars-vs-bills |title=Leonard Fournette, Shaq Lawson Ejected After Brawl in Jaguars vs. Bills |last=Zucker, Joseph |date=November 25, 2018 |website=Bleacher Report |access-date=November 26, 2018}}</ref> He was suspended one game the following day for the fight.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com/florida/story/jacksonville-jaguars-leonard-fournette-suspension-112618 |title=NFL suspends Jaguars RB Leonard Fournette 1 game without pay for sideline scuffle with Shaq Lawson |date=November 26, 2018 |website=The Associated Press |publisher=Fox Sports Florida |access-date=November 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFournette finished the 2018 season with 439 rushing yards and five rushing touchdowns to go along with 22 receptions for 185 receiving yards and a receiving touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/F/FourLe00.htm |title=Leonard Fournette 2018 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019 season===\nDuring a Week 4 26-24 road victory against the [[2019 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]], Fournette rushed for 225 yards, including an 81-yard rush, marking the first time in a single NFL game where he had over 200 rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jacksonville.com/sports/20190930/jaguars-vs-broncos-leonard-fournette-enjoys-career-day-what-we-learned-from-sundays-26-24-win |title=Jaguars vs. Broncos: Leonard Fournette enjoys career day; what we learned from Sunday's 26-24 win |last=Reid |first=John |date=September 30, 2019 |website=[[The Florida Times-Union]] |language=en |access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref> In the next game against the [[2019 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]], he rushed 23 times for 108 yards and his first rushing touchdown of the season in the 34-27 road loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127932 |title=McCaffrey scores 3 TDs, Panthers hold off Jaguars 34-27 |date=October 6, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=October 6, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> During Week 7 against the [[Cincinnati Bengals]], Fournette finished with 131 rushing yards as the Jaguars won 27-17. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127945 |title=Minshew, defense lead Jaguars over winless Bengals 27-17 |date=October 20, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=October 20, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 12 against the [[2019 Tennessee Titans|Tennessee Titans]], Fournette rushed 24 times for 97 yards and two touchdowns and caught nine passes for 62 yards in the 42\u201320 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128000 |title=Titans explode for 4 TDs in 6 plays, rout Jaguars 42-20 |date=November 24, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=November 24, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Overall, in the 2019 season, Fournette had 1,152 rushing yards and three rushing touchdowns to go along with 76 receptions for 522 receiving yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/F/FourLe00/gamelog/2019/ |title=Leonard Fournette 2019 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n! colspan=\"2\" | Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"| \n| Led the league\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n\n====Regular season====\n{| class= \"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games \n! colspan=\"5\"| Rushing \n! colspan=\"5\"| Receiving \n! colspan=\"2\"| Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Fum !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2017 NFL season|2017]] !! [[2017 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] \n| 13 || 13 || '''268''' || 1,040 || 3.9 || style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"|'''90T''' || '''9''' || 36 || 302 || '''8.4''' || 28 || '''1''' || '''2''' || 0\n|-\n! [[2018 NFL season|2018]] !! [[2018 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] \n| 8 || 8 || 133 || 439 || 3.3 || 25 || 5 || 22 || 185 || '''8.4''' || '''31''' || '''1''' || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[2019 NFL season|2019]] !! [[2019 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] \n| '''15''' || '''15''' || 265 || '''1,152''' || '''4.5''' || 81 || 3 || '''76''' || '''522''' || 6.9 || 27 || 0 || 1 || '''1'''\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"| Career !! 36 !! 36 !! 666 !! 2,631 !! 4.0 !! 90T !! 17 !! 134 !! 1,009 !! 7.5 !! 31 !! 2 !! 3 !! 1\n|-\n|}\n\n====Postseason====\n{| class= \"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games \n! colspan=\"5\"| Rushing \n! colspan=\"5\"| Receiving \n! colspan=\"2\"| Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Fum !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2017-18 NFL playoffs|2017]] !! [[2017 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]]\n| 3 || 3 || 70 || 242 || 3.5 || 18 || 4 || 7 || 44 || 6.3 || 12 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career || 3 || 3 || 70 || 242 || 3.5 || 18 || 4 || 7 || 44 || 6.3 || 12 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|}\n\n===NFL records===\n* Youngest player with a rushing touchdown of at least 90 yards (22 years, 263 days)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/Article/Jaguars-running-back-becomes-youngest-player-to-run-for-90-yards-in-NFL-history-108827791/Amp/ |title=Leonard Fournette's Jersey Headed To Hall of Fame |website=247sports.com |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Jaguars franchise records====\n* First player to score a scrimmage touchdown in each of his first six career games\n* First player to rush for at least 100 yards in his NFL debut\n* Longest rushing play: 90 yards (October 8, 2017 against the Pittsburgh Steelers)\n\n==Personal life==\nFournette's younger brother, Lanard, also played at [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lsusports.net/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=209872690 |title=Lanard Fournette |website=LSU Sports |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111215330/http://www.lsusports.net/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=209872690 |archive-date=November 11, 2018 |access-date=January 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/27752416/source-lsu-running-back-lanard-fournette-leaves-team |title=Source: LSU RB Lanard Fournette leaves team |last=Aschoff |first=Edward |date=October 2, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[LSU Tigers football statistical leaders]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [https://www.jaguars.com/team/players-roster/leonard-fournette/ Jacksonville Jaguars bio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180115124735/http://www.lsusports.net/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=209392529 LSU Tigers bio]\n\n{{Jacksonville Jaguars roster navbox}}\n{{Navboxes\n| list =\n{{USA Today OPOY}}\n{{2015 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{2017 NFL Draft}}\n{{JaguarsFirstPick}}\n{{Jaguars2017DraftPicks}}\n}}\n\n{{Portal bar|American football|Biography|College football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fournette, Leonard}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:American football running backs]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Jaguars players]]\n[[Category:LSU Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:St. Augustine High School (New Orleans) alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from New Orleans]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football running back}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n| name                = Leonard Fournette\n| image               = Leonard Fournette 2.png\n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Fournette in 2019\n| current_team        = Jacksonville Jaguars \n| number              = 27\n| position            = [[Running back]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1995|1|18}}\n| birth_place         = [[New Orleans, Louisiana]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 0\n| weight_lbs          = 228\n| high_school         = [[St. Augustine High School (New Orleans)|St. Augustine]]<br/>([[New Orleans|New Orleans, Louisiana]])\n| college             = [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]]\n| draftyear           = 2017\n| draftround          = 1\n| draftpick           = 4\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] ({{NFL Year|2017}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Active\n| highlights          = \n* Consensus [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2015 College Football All-America Team|2015]])\n* First-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] ([[2015 All-SEC football team|2015]])\n* Second-team All-SEC ([[2016 All-SEC football team|2016]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[USA Today All-USA high school football team|''USA Today'' High School All-American]] ([[2012 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2012]], [[2013 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2013]])\n| statleague = NFL\n| statweek   = \n| statseason = 2019\n| statlabel1   = [[Rushing yards]]\n| statvalue1   = 2,631\n| statlabel2   = [[Average|Rushing average]]\n| statvalue2   = 4.0\n| statlabel3   = [[Touchdown|Rushing touchdowns]]\n| statvalue3   = 17\n| statlabel4   = [[Reception (American football)|Receptions]]\n| statvalue4   = 134\n| statlabel5   = [[Receiving yards]] \n| statvalue5   = 1,009\n| statlabel6   = [[Touchdown|Receiving touchdowns]]\n| statvalue6   = 2\n| nflnew              = leonardfournette/2557973\n}}\n\n'''Leonard Joseph Fournette III''' (born January 18, 1995) is an [[American football]] [[running back]] for the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]], and was drafted by the Jaguars with the fourth overall pick in the [[2017 NFL Draft]]. Fournette was a consensus [[College Football All-America Team|All-America]] selection following his sophomore season in 2015, after setting school single-season records with 1,953 rushing yards and 22 rushing touchdowns, and leading the country with 162.8 rushing yards per game. Various experts regarded him as the best player in college football, comparing him to all-time great [[Herschel Walker]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Roser |first=Jerit |url=http://www.nola.com/lsu/index.ssf/2015/09/leonard_fournette_herschel_wal.html |title=Herschel Walker: Leonard Fournette 'is better than I was' |date=September 30, 2015 |work=The Times-Picayune |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Maisel |first=Ivan |url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/13817380/lsu-leonard-fournette-lebron-best-kind-different |title=Leonard Fournette: The best kind of different |date=October 7, 2015 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFournette joined the Tigers with near-unprecedented hype in 2014 after an outstanding career at [[St. Augustine High School (New Orleans)|St. Augustine High School]] in [[New Orleans]], winning the [[USA Today High School Football Offensive Player of the Year|2013 ''USA Today'' High School Football Offensive Player of the Year]] and being named the No. 1 overall recruit in 2014 senior class according to [[ESPN]], ''[[247Sports.com]]'', and [[CBS Sports]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Yellin |first=Lyons |url=http://www.nola.com/recruiting/index.ssf/2013/04/st_augustines_leonard_fournett.html |title=ESPN names St. Augustine's Leonard Fournette nation's No. 1 recruit |date=April 18, 2013 |work=The Times-Picayune |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> Fournette's brother, Lanard, is a former [[running back]] at [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]].\n\n==Early years==\nRaised in the [[7th Ward of New Orleans]], Fournette grew up in a troubled area that was often affected by violence and gang activity, especially after [[Hurricane Katrina]] hit in 2005. Fournette credited Katrina as kick-starting his football career after he moved to Houston and back within a year because of the hurricane evacuation. When he came back to New Orleans he played [[high school football|football]] at [[St. Augustine High School (New Orleans)|St. Augustine High School]], and competed in track and field.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Boudwin |first=Julie |url=http://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2017/01/leonard_fournette_gives_back_t_1.html |title=Leonard Fournette gives back to St. Augustine on his 22nd birthday |work=NOLA.com |access-date=February 3, 2018 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204123925/https://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2017/01/leonard_fournette_gives_back_t_1.html |archive-date=February 4, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> His [[200 metres]] regional mark of 21.57 seconds is fastest in 4A, and his 10.68 in the [[100 metres]] is only .02 off the best time. He also competed in the [[4 \u00d7 100 metres relay]] and [[4 \u00d7 200 metres relay]]. On the varsity football team, he was a starter since his freshman year and compiled 7,619 rushing yards and 88 rushing touchdowns for his career.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/jacksonville-jaguars/post/_/id/25487 |title=Jaguars star Leonard Fournette forges bond with state champs |last=DiRocco |first=Michael |date=May 31, 2018 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2019}}</ref> He rushed for more than 2,500 yards and 30 touchdowns his freshman season, and became the first-ever freshman to earn a scholarship offer from [[LSU Tigers football|Louisiana State]].<ref name=\"ESPN_Scarborough\">{{Cite news |last=Scarborough |first=Alex |url=http://espn.go.com/colleges/alabama/story/_/id/8090719/2014-running-back-leonard-fournette-overcome-adversity-excel-life |title=2014 running back Leonard Fournette has overcome adversity to excel in life |date=June 25, 2012 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> His sophomore year ended with 1,900 yards rushing and 27 touchdowns. As a junior, he registered 2,135 rushing yards and 31 touchdowns and was an LFCA Class 4A First-Team All-State honoree. In his senior year, Fournette ran for 1,792 yards and 16 touchdowns and added 45 receptions for 745 yards and six scores. Early in the season, he had a heralded performance with two touchdowns and 262 yards rushing against [[Malachi Dupre]]'s [[John Curtis Christian High School|John Curtis Christian]], which was nationally televised by [[ESPN2]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hamilton |first=Gerry |url=http://insider.espn.go.com/college-sports/recruiting/football/story/_/id/9791414/week-was-in-football-recruiting |title=Fournette breaks out: Nation's top recruit Leonard Fournette puts on a show on ESPN2 |date=October 8, 2013 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref> St. Augustine ended the season with a 9\u20132 record and an appearance in the [[Louisiana High School Athletic Association|LHSAA]] Division I semifinal game, where they were upset 31\u201328 by [[Archbishop Rummel High School]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Derry |first=Jim |url=http://highschoolsports.nola.com/news/article/5650481414329799202/fifth-seeded-rummel-shocks-st-augustine-31-28/ |title=Fifth-seeded Rummel shocks St. Augustine, 31\u201328 |date=December 1, 2013 |work=The Times-Picayune |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> Fournette was named [[Mr. Football Award (Louisiana)|Louisiana's 2013 Mr. Football]] by the Louisiana Sports Writers Association, and also was selected as an All-American by ''[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]'' and ''[[USA Today]]'', as well as ''USA Today'' Offensive Player of the Year, the first from Louisiana since [[Ryan Perrilloux]] in 2004. After the season, Fournette participated in the [[Under Armour All-America Game]] where he caught a 36-yard touchdown pass and rushed for 43 yards on nine carries.\n\nUnanimously regarded as the best running back prospect of his class, Fournette was one of the most highly recruited players ever to come out of Louisiana. [[ESPN]] ranked him as the No. 1 recruit in the class of 2014,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/football/recruiting/playerrankings/_/class/2014/order/true |title=2014 ESPN 300 |website=ESPN.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821174952/http://www.espn.com/college-sports/football/recruiting/playerrankings/_/class/2014/order/true |archive-date=August 21, 2016 |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> as did [[Scout.com]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.scout.com/topic/players?s=73&category=Football%20Recruiting&league=HS&classYear=2014 |title=2014 High School Recruits Ranking |website=Scout.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151008014041/https://scout.com/topic/players/?s=73&category=Football%20Recruiting&league=HS&classYear=2014 |archive-date=October 8, 2015 |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> At the 2014 Under Armour All-America Game, Fournette announced his decision to attend [[LSU Tigers football|Louisiana State University]] (LSU).<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tyson |first=Derek |url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/recruiting/football/story/_/id/10232850/top-recruits-make-commitments-armour-all-america-game |title=Leonard Fournette commits to LSU |date=January 3, 2014 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nFournette attended and played college football for LSU from 2014\u20132016 under head coaches [[Les Miles]] and [[Ed Orgeron]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/leonard-fournette-1.html |title=Leonard Fournette College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Freshman season===\nFournette's college career was preceded by very high expectations and hype, and he was often called \"the next [[Adrian Peterson]]\".<ref name=\"cbssports.com\">{{Cite news |last=Fornelli |first=Tom |url=http://www.cbssports.com/collegefootball/eye-on-college-football/24693042/les-miles-wants-to-temper-the-fournette-hype-he-helped-create |title=Les Miles wants to temper the Fournette hype he helped create |date=September 3, 2014 |work=CBSSports.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"nola.com\">{{Cite news |last=Duncan |first=Jeff |url=http://www.nola.com/lsu/index.ssf/2014/08/hold_the_heisman_leonard_fourn.html |title=Leonard Fournette's collegiate debut is more fizzle than sizzle |date=August 31, 2014 |work=The Times-Picayune |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> In his collegiate debut against the [[2014 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin Badgers]] on August 30, 2014, Fournette ran for 18 yards on eight carries.<ref name=\"nola.com\" /> After the game, LSU head coach Les Miles downplayed the Fournette hype. \"First games are not to be comparable to his 30th game,\" said Miles. \"Expectations are unrealistic.\"<ref name=\"cbssports.com\" />\nIn his second game, against the [[2014 Sam Houston State Bearkats football team|Sam Houston State Bearkats]], Fournette rushed for 92 yards on 13 attempts and scored his first collegiate rushing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-09-06-louisiana-state.html |title=Sam Houston State at Louisiana State Box Score, September 6, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> In the fifth week of the season, the [[2014 New Mexico State Aggies football team|New Mexico State Aggies]] traveled to [[Tiger Stadium (LSU)|Death Valley]] to face the #17 LSU Tigers, and Fournette ran for 122 yards on 18 carries and scored two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-09-27-louisiana-state.html |title=New Mexico State at Louisiana State Box Score, September 27, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> This effort put Fournette at the top of the Tigers' rushing list for the season.<ref name=\"m.espn.go.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://m.espn.com/ncf/playergamelog?playerId=559752&season=2014&wjb |title=Leonard Fournette 2014 Game Log |website=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> On October 11 against SEC [[Florida\u2013LSU football rivalry|rival]] [[2014 Florida Gators football team|Florida]], Fournette rushed the ball 27 times for 140 yards and two touchdowns to help LSU secure a 30\u201327 last-second win in [[Ben Hill Griffin Stadium|The Swamp]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-10-11-florida.html |title=LSU at Florida Box Score, October 11, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> Against undefeated and #3 [[2014 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]], who led the nation in stopping the run, Fournette shook off an early goal line fumble and rushed 23 times for 113 yards to go along with two receptions for 41 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-10-25-louisiana-state.html |title=Ole Miss at Louisiana State Box Score, October 25, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> LSU ran the ball 12 times for 92 yards on a 13-play, 95-yard touchdown drive to upset the Rebels by a score of 10\u20137 in Death Valley.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Martel |first=Brett |url=http://www.cbssports.com/collegefootball/gametracker/recap/NCAAF_20141025_MISS@LSU/no-24-lsu-upends-no3-mississippi-10-7 |title=No. 24 LSU upends No.3 Mississippi, 10\u20137 |date=October 26, 2014 |work=CBSSports.com |access-date=December 12, 2016 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Fournette finished the season against [[2014 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]] in the [[2014 Music City Bowl]] with 11 carries for 143 yards and two touchdowns. In addition, he had a 100-yard kickoff return for a touchdown in the loss to the Fighting Irish.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sparks |first=Adam |url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/college/2014/12/30/lsu-leonard-fournette-sizzles-music-city-bowl-loss-notre-dame/21084229/ |title=LSU's Leonard Fournette sizzles in Music City Bowl |date=December 30, 2014 |work=The Tennessean |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-12-30-louisiana-state.html |title=Music City Bowl \u2013 Notre Dame vs Louisiana State Box Score, December 30, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Sophomore season===\n\nFournette started his sophomore season with a strong performance of 159 rushing yards and three touchdowns against [[2015 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team|Mississippi State]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-09-12-mississippi-state.html |title=LSU at Mississippi State Box Score, September 12, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, a victory over [[2015 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]], he finished with 228 rushing yards and three touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-09-19-louisiana-state.html |title=Auburn at Louisiana State Box Score, September 19, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> He rushed for a career-high 244 yards and two touchdowns against [[2015 Syracuse Orange football team|Syracuse]] in the [[Carrier Dome]], six yards shy of tying [[Alley Broussard]]'s school record of 250 yards against [[2004 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]] in 2004.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Moormann |first=Dave |url=http://www.dailycomet.com/article/20041122/SPORTS/411220315 |title=LSU's ground attack overcomes sluggish passing game |date=November 22, 2004 |work=The Daily Comet |access-date=December 12, 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928045308/http://www.dailycomet.com/article/20041122/SPORTS/411220315 |archive-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref> Fournette had an 87-yard touchdown run nullified by an [[illegal formation]] call late in the game.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=400603849 |title=Leonard Fournette first LSU RB to run for 200 yards in consecutive games |date=September 26, 2015 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> The following week, against [[2015 Eastern Michigan Eagles football team|Eastern Michigan]], Fournette rushed for 233 yards, becoming the first player in [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC) history to rush for 200 or more yards in three straight games.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/statsinfo/post/_/id/110157/lsus-fournette-on-an-unprecedented-run |title=LSU's Leonard Fournette on an unprecedented run |date=October 6, 2015 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> Against [[2015 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team|Western Kentucky]], Fournette ran for 150 yards, his ninth consecutive 100+ yards rushing game, a streak that dated back to the [[2014 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]] game in late November 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-10-24-louisiana-state.html |title=Western Kentucky at Louisiana State Box Score, October 24, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> He tied a school record originally established by [[Charles Alexander (running back)|Charles Alexander]] in [[1978 LSU Tigers football team|1978]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.seccountry.com/louisiana-state/lsu-running-back-leonard-fournette-matches-school-record-consecutive-100-yard-rushing-games |title=LSU running back Leonard Fournette matches school record consecutive 100-yard rushing games |last=Harris |first=Terrance |date=October 24, 2015 |website=SEC Country |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> Fournette's streak ended the next game against [[Alabama\u2013LSU football rivalry|rival]] [[2015 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]], the nation's best rushing defense, at [[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]]. He was held to 31 yards on 19 attempts, as the Crimson Tide handed LSU its first loss of the season.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/recap?id=400603905 |title=Derrick Henry (210 yards, 3 TDs) rolls as Bama contains Leonard Fournette, LSU |date=November 8, 2015 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=April 3, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In the [[2015 Texas Bowl]], Fournette ran for 212 yards and scored five total touchdowns as the Tigers defeated [[2015 Texas Tech Red Raiders football team|Texas Tech]], 56\u201327.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nola.com/lsu/index.ssf/2015/12/lsu_leonard_fournette_trample.html |title=LSU, Leonard Fournette trample Texas Tech in Texas Bowl, 56\u201327 |last=Kleinpeter |first=Jim |date=December 29, 2015 |website=The Times-Picayune |access-date=January 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn his sophomore season, Fournette set school records with 1,953 rushing yards and 22 rushing touchdowns. With an average of 162.8 rushing yards per game, he won the NCAA rushing title, awarded to the player with the highest rushing yards per game average each season.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kleinpeter |first=Jim |url=http://www.nola.com/lsu/index.ssf/2016/01/leonard_fournette_wins_ncaa_ru.html |title=Leonard Fournette wins NCAA rushing title |date=January 12, 2016 |work=The Times-Picayune |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> He finished sixth in [[Heisman Trophy]] voting, earning 110 points. He earned consensus [[College Football All-America Team|All-America]] honors as he was named to the first team by three official selectors: the [[Associated Press]] (AP),<ref>{{Cite news |last=Russo |first=Ralph D. |url=http://collegefootball.ap.org/article/heisman-trophy-winner-henry-highlights-ap-all-america-team |title=Heisman Trophy Winner Henry Highlights AP All-America Team |date=December 13, 2015 |access-date=December 12, 2016 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> the [[Walter Camp Football Foundation]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Carbone |first=Al |url=http://waltercamp.org/126th-walter-camp-all-america-teams-announced/ |title=126th Walter Camp All-America Teams |date=December 10, 2015 |access-date=December 12, 2016 |publisher=Walter Camp Football Foundation}}</ref> and the [[Football Writers Association of America]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sportswriters.net/fwaa/news/2015/allamerica151214.html |title=2015 AutoNation FWAA All-America Team Unveiled |date=December 14, 2015 |access-date=December 12, 2016 |publisher=Football Writers Association of America}}</ref> SEC coaches,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kalland |first=Robby |url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/2015-coaches-all-sec-team-alabama-leads-the-way-with-10-selections/ |title=2015 Coaches' All-SEC Team: Alabama leads the way with 10 selections |date=December 8, 2015 |access-date=December 12, 2016 |publisher=CBS Sports}}</ref> the [[Associated Press]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://collegefootball.ap.org/article/2015-associated-press-all-sec-football-team |title=2015 Associated Press All-SEC football team |date=December 14, 2015 |access-date=December 12, 2016 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> and ESPN.com<ref>{{Cite news |last=Aschoff |first=Edward |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/sec/post/_/id/111828/the-espn-com-2015-all-sec-team |title=2015 ESPN.com All-SEC team: Derrick Henry, Leonard Fournette lead the way |date=December 9, 2015 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> each named Fournette to their All-SEC first team.\n\n===Junior season===\nEntering his junior season, Fournette was expected to contend for the [[Heisman Trophy]], and was one of the preseason favorites to win the award.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Chiusano |first=Anthony |url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/football/hand-him/2016-08-28/heisman-watch-early-favorites-take-home-trophy-2016 |title=Heisman Watch: Early favorites to take home the trophy in 2016 |date=August 29, 2016 |work=NCAA.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Ellis |first=Zach |url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2015/12/14/heisman-trophy-2016-race-way-too-early |title=Heisman Watch: A way-too-early look at the 2016 Heisman race |date=December 14, 2015 |work=Sports Illustrated |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> During a scrimmage game prior to the [[2016 LSU Tigers football team|2016 season]], Fournette sustained a [[high ankle sprain]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Dellenger |first=Ross |url=http://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_e9e4ff42-7f46-11e6-930a-1b2392133476.html |title=Details of Leonard Fournette's ankle injury? ESPN's Dr. Jerry Punch explains... |date=September 20, 2016 |work=The Advocate |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Patterson |first=Chip |url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/lsus-worst-nightmare-leonard-fournette-in-boot-following-ankle-injury/ |title=Scary scenario for LSU: Leonard Fournette in boot following ankle injury |date=August 16, 2016 |access-date=December 12, 2016 |publisher=CBS Sports}}</ref> but was well enough to return for the season opener against [[2016 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]] at [[Lambeau Field]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2016-09-03-wisconsin.html |title=LSU vs Wisconsin Box Score, September 3, 2016 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> Late in the game against Wisconsin, he bruised the same ankle and missed the next week's game against [[2016 Jacksonville State Gamecocks football team|Jacksonville State]] as a result. He re-injured it against SEC West rival [[2016 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] on September 24 in a 101-yard rushing effort, causing him to miss the next two games.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Dellenger |first=Ross |url=http://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_31a03b84-89bb-11e6-a094-eb0773fc5e84.html |title=LSU Practice Report: Still no Leonard Fournette, offensive line rotation and more |date=October 3, 2016 |work=The Advocate |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> On October 22, his first game back, Fournette rushed for 284 yards and three touchdowns against [[2016 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]] to set a new single-game school record for rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ching |first=David |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/sec/post/_/id/122721/welcome-back-leonard-fournette-smashes-lsu-rushing-record-in-return |title=Welcome back, Leonard: Fournette smashes LSU rushing record in return |date=October 22, 2016 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> His school record was surpassed later in the season by [[Derrius Guice]] by one yard. With his ankle still not fully healed, Fournette was not expected to play against [[2016 Florida Gators football team|Florida]] on November 19, and did not suit up for pregame warm-ups. However, after a pregame scuffle between the teams in which Fournette shoved a Florida assistant coach,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Curtis |first=Charles |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ftw/2016/11/19/lsus-leonard-fournette-florida-assistant-coach-appear-to-be-involved-in-pregame-skirmish/94126590/ |title=LSU's Leonard Fournette, Florida assistant coach part of pregame skirmish |date=November 19, 2016 |work=USA Today |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> LSU head coach [[Ed Orgeron]] granted him permission to play. Still visibly bothered by the injury, he managed only 40 yards on 12 carries and did not play in the fourth quarter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2016-11-19-louisiana-state.html |title=Florida at Louisiana State Box Score, November 19, 2016 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> Due to the injury, he did not travel with the team to [[College Station, Texas|College Station]] to face [[2016 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]] in the final game of the regular season.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Dellenger |first=Ross |url=http://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_7bf7d420-b1b2-11e6-851e-f7b6064f27ef.html |title=Source: LSU's Leonard Fournette did not make trip, won't play vs. Texas A&M on Thanksgiving |date=November 23, 2016 |work=The Advocate |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> He finished his junior season having carried 129 times for 843 yards and eight touchdowns in seven games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/leonard-fournette-1/gamelog/2016/ |title=Leonard Fournette 2016 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn December 5, 2016, Fournette announced his intention to enter the [[2017 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Goodbread |first=Chase |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000751840/article/leonard-fournette-intends-to-enter-2017-nfl-draft |title=Leonard Fournette intends to enter 2017 NFL Draft |date=December 5, 2016 |work=NFL.com |access-date=December 5, 2015}}</ref> To avoid injury, his coach told him to skip the [[2016 Citrus Bowl (December)|2016 Citrus Bowl]], which LSU won over [[2016 Louisville Cardinals football team|Louisville]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ching |first=David |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/18293243/leonard-fournette-lsu-tigers-play-buffalo-wild-wings-citrus-bowl |title=Leonard Fournette won't play Buffalo Wild Wings Citrus Bowl |date=December 16, 2016 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=December 16, 2016}}</ref> Fournette finished his college career having rushed for 3,830 yards, the fourth-most by a player in LSU history behind [[Charles Alexander (running back)|Charles Alexander]], [[Dalton Hilliard]], and [[Kevin Faulk]]. His 40 rushing touchdowns are tied for third most in school history with Alexander and behind Hilliard and Faulk.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/louisiana-state/rushing.html |title=LSU Fighting Tigers Rushing |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=4 style=\"text-align: center; font-weight:bold; background-color:#FDD023; color:#461D7C;\"| Leonard Fournette !!colspan=5| Rushing !!colspan=3|Receiving\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! GP !! GS !! Att !! Yards !! Avg !! Long !! TDs !! Rec !! Yards !! TDs\n|-\n| [[2014 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2014]] || [[2014 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]] || 13 || 6 || 187 || 1,034 || 5.5 || 89 || 10 || 7 || 127 || 0\n|-\n| [[2015 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2015]] || [[2015 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]] || 11 || 11 || 271 || 1,953 || 6.4 || 87 || 22 || 18 || 209 || 1\n|-\n| [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2016]] || [[2016 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]] || 7 || 7 || 129 || 843 || 6.5 || 78 || 8 || 15 || 146 || 0\n|- style=\"background:#555; font-weight:bold; color:white;\"\n| colspan=2 | College Totals || 31 || 24 || 616 || 3,830 || 6.2 || 89 || 40 || 40 || 482 || 1\n|}\n\n''Source:''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/leonard-fournette-1.html |title=Leonard Fournette College Stats |website=Sports-Reference.com |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nComing out of college, Fournette was highly touted as a top ten pick in the upcoming draft and was ranked as the third best prospect going into the NFL Combine. He arrived at the NFL combine weighing in five pounds heavier than his playing weight in college and opted to only participate in the vertical and 40-yard dash. At LSU's Pro Day, he opted to only partake in positional drills. He was ranked the top overall running back prospect by NFLDraftScout.com, and second behind [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State's]] [[Dalvin Cook]] by [[Pro Football Focus]] and ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=130694&draftyear=2017&genpos=RB |title=*Leonard Fournette, DS #1 RB, LSU |website=nfldraftscout.com |access-date=May 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.profootballfocus.com/draft-college-football-top-32-prospects-for-2017-nfl-draft/ |title=Top 32 Prospects for the 2017 NFL Draft |date=November 30, 2016 |website=profootballfocus.com |access-date=May 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/2017-nfl-draft-position-rankings |title=2017 NFL draft rankings: Top prospects by position |last=Burke |first=Chris |date=April 24, 2017 |website=si.com |access-date=May 10, 2017}}</ref>\n{{external media\n| video1 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/0ap3000000796763/Leonard-Fournette-2017-Combine-Workout Fournette's NFL Combine workout]\n| video2 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/0ap3000000789630/Leonard-Fournette-runs-official-4-51-40-yard-dash Leonard Fournette's 40-yard dash]\n| video3 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/0ap3000000797912/Leonard-Fournette-s-Pro-Day-highlights Fournette's Pro Day highlights]\n}}\n\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 0\u00bd\n|       weight = 240\n|         dash = 4.51\n|    ten split = 1.59\n| twenty split = 2.65\n|      shuttle = \n|   cone drill = \n|     vertical = 28\u00bd\n|     broad ft = \n|     broad in = \n|        bench = \n|    wonderlic = \n|     arm span = {{frac|31|5|8}}\n|    hand span = {{frac|9|1|4}}\n|         note = All values from [[NFL Combine]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/leonard-fournette?id=2557973 |title=Combine Player Profiles - Leonard Fournette |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.draftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=130694&draftyear=2017&genpos=rb |title=*Leonard Fournette -\u00a0LSU,\u00a0RB\u00a0:\u00a02017 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile |website=Draft Scout |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920200114/http://www.draftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=130694&draftyear=2017&genpos=rb |archive-date=September 20, 2018 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/0ap3000000796763/Leonard-Fournette-2017-Combine-Workout |title=Leonard Fournette 2017 Combine Workout |website=www.nfl.com |access-date=August 20, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{external media\n| video1 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/0ap3000000803362/Jaguars-select-Leonard-Fournette-No-4-in-the-2017-NFL-Draft Jaguars select Fournette fourth overall]\n| video2 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/0ap3000000803150/Leonard-Fournette-arrives-at-the-NFL-Draft-with-his-parents Fournette arrives at 2017 NFL Draft]\n}}\nThe [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] selected Fournette fourth overall in the [[2017 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000803317/article/jaguars-select-rb-leonard-fournette-with-fourth-pick |title=Jaguars select RB Leonard Fournette with fourth pick |last=Orr |first=Conor |date=April 27, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref> He was the first running back taken in that year's draft.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2017/draft.htm |title=2017 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> On May 17, 2017, the Jacksonville Jaguars signed Fournette to a four-year, $27 million contract with a $18 million signing bonus.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000809518/article/leonard-fournette-signs-rookie-deal-with-jaguars |title=Leonard Fournette signs rookie deal with Jaguars |last=Patra |first=Kevin |website=NFL.com |access-date=May 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n\n===2017 season===\nFournette made his regular season debut on September 10, 2017, against the [[2017 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]] at [[NRG Stadium]]. He rushed for 100 yards and a touchdown on 26 carries as the Jaguars won 29\u20137.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/redskins/fournette-strong-defense-lead-jaguars-over-texans-29-7/2017/09/10/e47f2fcc-9666-11e7-af6a-6555caaeb8dc_story.html |title=Fournette, strong defense lead Jaguars over Texans 29\u20137 |last=Rieken |first=Kristie |website=[[The Washington Post]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914180127/https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/redskins/fournette-strong-defense-lead-jaguars-over-texans-29-7/2017/09/10/e47f2fcc-9666-11e7-af6a-6555caaeb8dc_story.html |archive-date=September 14, 2017 |access-date=September 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709100htx.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Houston Texans \u2013 September 10th, 2017 |website=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]] |access-date=September 14, 2017}}</ref> In Week 4, against the [[2017 New York Jets season|New York Jets]], Fournette recorded a 10-yard reception in the first quarter for his first career receiving touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201710010nyj.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at New York Jets \u2013 October 1st, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 5, 2017}}</ref> In Week 5 against the [[2017 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], Fournette posted an impressive performance with 181 rushing yards, including a Jaguars franchise-record 90-yard run in the fourth quarter, and two touchdowns as the Jaguars won 30\u20139.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Graves |first=Will |url=http://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/article_12a234e6-ac68-11e7-ad18-b3c9625a3132.html |title=Leonard Fournette's 181 yards, 2 touchdowns cap off Jaguars' defense-fueled 31\u20139 win over Steelers |date=October 8, 2017 |work=The Advocate |access-date=October 8, 2017 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 6 against the [[2017 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]], Fournette carried 21 times for 130 yards, including a 75-yard touchdown run on the Jaguars' first play from scrimmage. He left the game in the fourth quarter with a minor ankle injury as the Jaguars lost to the Rams, 27\u201317.<ref>{{Cite news |last=DiRocco |first=Michael |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/21036865/jacksonville-jaguars-rb-leonard-fournette-sprains-ankle-loss-los-angeles-rams |title=Leonard Fournette sprains ankle |date=October 15, 2017 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=October 15, 2017}}</ref> Because of the ankle injury, he was ruled out for Week 7. Following a bye week, more trouble arose as Fournette was declared inactive for Week 9 against the [[2017 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]] as he violated team rules.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000871746/article/leonard-fournette-out-for-jaguars-after-rule-violation |title=Leonard Fournette out for Jaguars after rule violation |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=November 5, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=November 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 13 games and starts, Fournette finished his rookie year with 1,040 rushing yards and nine rushing touchdowns along with 302 receiving yards and a receiving touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/F/FourLe00/gamelog/2017/ |title=Leonard Fournette 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> He was ranked 58th by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2018]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2018/0ap3000000933651/Top-100-Players-of-2018-Leonard-Fournette-No-58 |title='Top 100 Players of 2018': Jacksonville Jaguars running back Leonard Fournette |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Jaguars finished the 2017 season with a 10\u20136 record, clinching the [[AFC South]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/jax/2017.htm |title=2017 Jacksonville Jaguars Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2017\u201318_NFL_playoffs#AFC:_Jacksonville_Jaguars_10,_Buffalo_Bills_3|Wild Card Round]] against the [[2017 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], Fournette struggled, rushing for 57 yards on 21 carries as the Jaguars won 10\u20133.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801070jax.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Buffalo Bills at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 January 7th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2017\u201318_NFL_playoffs#AFC:_Jacksonville_Jaguars_45,_Pittsburgh_Steelers_42|Divisional Round]] against the [[2017 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], he briefly left the game with an ankle injury, but returned and finished with 109 yards and three touchdowns as the Jaguars won 45\u201342.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.duluthnewstribune.com/sports/4388008-jaguars-withstand-late-rally-topple-steelers-45-42 |title=Jaguars withstand late rally, topple Steelers 45-42 |date=January 14, 2018 |website=[[Duluth News Tribune]] |language=en |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref> The following week, in the [[2017\u201318_NFL_playoffs#AFC_Championship_Game:_New_England_Patriots_24,_Jacksonville_Jaguars_20|AFC Championship]] against the [[2017 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], Fournette ran for 76 yards and a touchdown, but the Jaguars lost 24\u201320.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801210nwe.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 Jacksonville Jaguars at New England Patriots \u2013 January 21st, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018 season===\nFournette injured his hamstring during the season-opening 20-15 victory against the [[2018 New York Giants season|New York Giants]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24625351 |title=Jags RB Fournette out with hamstring injury |last=DiRocco |first=Mike |date=September 9, 2018 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2019}}</ref> He missed the next two games before returning against the [[2018 New York Jets season|New York Jets]], where he aggravated the injury and was ruled out indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/leonard-fournette-out-indefinitely-after-re-aggravating-hamstring-injury-sunday/ |title=Leonard Fournette out indefinitely after aggravating hamstring injury Sunday |last=Dubin |first=Jared |date=October 1, 2018 |website=CBSSports.com |access-date=November 26, 2018}}</ref> After missing four more games, he returned against the division rival [[2018 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], rushing for 53 yards and a touchdown with 56 receiving yards and a receiving touchdown as the Jaguars narrowly lost 29\u201326.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201811110clt.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Indianapolis Colts - November 11th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=September 20, 2019}}</ref> Against the [[2018 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], Fournette had his best game of the season, rushing for 95 yards and two touchdowns. However, after a [[Donte Moncrief]] reception that was initially ruled a touchdown in the third quarter, Fournette got into a fistfight with Bills defender [[Shaq Lawson]] as part of a brawl that broke out between the Jaguars and Bills, and the two were subsequently ejected from the game. Without Fournette, the Jaguars lost 24\u201321.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2807726-leonard-fournette-shaq-lawson-ejected-after-brawl-in-jaguars-vs-bills |title=Leonard Fournette, Shaq Lawson Ejected After Brawl in Jaguars vs. Bills |last=Zucker, Joseph |date=November 25, 2018 |website=Bleacher Report |access-date=November 26, 2018}}</ref> He was suspended one game the following day for the fight.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com/florida/story/jacksonville-jaguars-leonard-fournette-suspension-112618 |title=NFL suspends Jaguars RB Leonard Fournette 1 game without pay for sideline scuffle with Shaq Lawson |date=November 26, 2018 |website=The Associated Press |publisher=Fox Sports Florida |access-date=November 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFournette finished the 2018 season with 439 rushing yards and five rushing touchdowns to go along with 22 receptions for 185 receiving yards and a receiving touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/F/FourLe00.htm |title=Leonard Fournette 2018 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019 season===\nDuring a Week 4 26-24 road victory against the [[2019 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]], Fournette rushed for 225 yards, including an 81-yard rush, marking the first time in a single NFL game where he had over 200 rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jacksonville.com/sports/20190930/jaguars-vs-broncos-leonard-fournette-enjoys-career-day-what-we-learned-from-sundays-26-24-win |title=Jaguars vs. Broncos: Leonard Fournette enjoys career day; what we learned from Sunday's 26-24 win |last=Reid |first=John |date=September 30, 2019 |website=[[The Florida Times-Union]] |language=en |access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref> In the next game against the [[2019 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]], he rushed 23 times for 108 yards and his first rushing touchdown of the season in the 34-27 road loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127932 |title=McCaffrey scores 3 TDs, Panthers hold off Jaguars 34-27 |date=October 6, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=October 6, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> During Week 7 against the [[Cincinnati Bengals]], Fournette finished with 131 rushing yards as the Jaguars won 27-17. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127945 |title=Minshew, defense lead Jaguars over winless Bengals 27-17 |date=October 20, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=October 20, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 12 against the [[2019 Tennessee Titans|Tennessee Titans]], Fournette rushed 24 times for 97 yards and two touchdowns and caught nine passes for 62 yards in the 42\u201320 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128000 |title=Titans explode for 4 TDs in 6 plays, rout Jaguars 42-20 |date=November 24, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=November 24, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Overall, in the 2019 season, Fournette had 1,152 rushing yards and three rushing touchdowns to go along with 76 receptions for 522 receiving yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/F/FourLe00/gamelog/2019/ |title=Leonard Fournette 2019 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n! colspan=\"2\" | Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"| \n| Led the league\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n\n====Regular season====\n{| class= \"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games \n! colspan=\"5\"| Rushing \n! colspan=\"5\"| Receiving \n! colspan=\"2\"| Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Rec 