 \n| caption        =\n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1998|2|17}}<ref name=SW>{{Soccerway|id=306383|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_place    = \n| height         = \n| position       = [[Midfielder]]<ref>{{UEFA player|id=250063143|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| currentclub    = Dinamo-BGU\n| clubnumber     = \n| youthyears1    = \n| youthclubs1    = \n| collegeyears1  = \n| college1       = \n| collegecaps1   = | collegegoals1 = \n| years1         = 2014\u20132019\n| clubs1         = [[FC Energetik-BGU Minsk|Zorka-BDU]]\n| caps1          = 55\n| goals1         = 47\n| years2         = 2020\u2013\n| clubs2         = Dinamo-BGU\n| caps2          = 0\n| goals2         = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2013\u20132015\n| nationalteam1  = {{Nwftu|17|Belarus}}\n| nationalcaps1  = 8\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2019\u2013\n| nationalteam2  = [[Belarus women's national football team|Belarus]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 1\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| pcupdate = 3 November 2019\n| ntupdate = 8 October 2019\n}}\n'''Darya Stezhko''' (born 17 February 1998) is a Belarusian [[women's association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Belarusian Premier League (women)|Belarusian Premier League]] club Dinamo-BGU and the [[Belarus women's national football team|Belarus women's national team]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stezhko, Darya}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women's association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Belarusian women's footballers]]\n[[Category:Belarus women's international footballers]]\n[[Category:FC Energetik-BGU Minsk<!-- women --> players]]\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Darya_Stezhko"}
{"title_page": "HMNZS Hawea (1975)", "text_new": "{{other ships|HMNZS Hawea}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=September 2016}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=\n|Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=[[New Zealand]]\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|New Zealand|naval}}\n|Ship name=\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship owner=\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder=[[Brooke Marine]], Britain\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=1975\n|Ship decommissioned=1991\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship identification=[[Pennant number]]: P3571\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Ship class=[[Lake-class patrol boat|Lake-class]] inshore [[patrol vessel]]\n|Ship displacement=*105 tons standard\n*135 tons full load\n|Ship length={{convert|107.8|ft|m|abbr=on}} \n|Ship beam={{convert|20|ft|m|abbr=on}} \n|Ship draught={{convert|11.1|ft|m|abbr=on}} \n|Ship propulsion=2 \u00d7 Paxman 12Y JCM diesels, 3,000 hp, 2 shafts\n|Ship speed={{convert|25|kn}}\n|Ship range={{convert|3000|nmi}}\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship complement=21\n|Ship sensors=*Navigation radar:\n*Racal Decca 916 I Band\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*2 \u00d7 12.7mm machine guns\n*1 \u00d7 81mm mortar\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''HMNZS ''Hawea''''' was a [[Lake-class patrol boat|Lake-class]] inshore [[patrol vessel]] of the [[Royal New Zealand Navy]]. It was commissioned in 1975 and decommissioned in 1991.\n\n''Hawea'' was one of three ships of this name to serve in the Royal New Zealand Navy and is named after [[Lake H\u0101wea]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Patrol boats of the Royal New Zealand Navy]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* McDougall, R J (1989) ''New Zealand Naval Vessels.'' Page 98-100. Government Printing Office. {{ISBN|978-0-477-01399-4}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hawea}}\n[[Category:Lake-class patrol vessels]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Lowestoft]]\n\n\n{{Mil-ship-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=September 2016}}\n{{otherships|HMNZS Hawea}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=\n|Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=[[New Zealand]]\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|New Zealand|naval}}\n|Ship name=\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship owner=\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder=[[Brooke Marine]], Britain\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=1975\n|Ship decommissioned=1991\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship identification=[[Pennant number]]: P3571\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Ship class=[[Lake-class patrol boat|Lake-class]] inshore [[patrol vessel]]\n|Ship displacement=*105 tons standard\n*135 tons full load\n|Ship length={{convert|107.8|ft|m|abbr=on}} \n|Ship beam={{convert|20|ft|m|abbr=on}} \n|Ship draught={{convert|11.1|ft|m|abbr=on}} \n|Ship propulsion=2 \u00d7 Paxman 12Y JCM diesels, 3,000 hp, 2 shafts\n|Ship speed={{convert|25|kn}}\n|Ship range={{convert|3000|nmi}}\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship complement=21\n|Ship sensors=*Navigation radar:\n*Racal Decca 916 I Band\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*2 \u00d7 12.7mm machine guns\n*1 \u00d7 81mm mortar\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''HMNZS ''Hawea''''' was a [[Lake-class patrol boat|Lake-class]] inshore [[patrol vessel]] of the [[Royal New Zealand Navy]]. It was commissioned in 1975 and decommissioned in 1991.\n\n''Hawea'' was one of three ships of this name to serve in the Royal New Zealand Navy and is named after [[Lake Hawea]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Patrol boats of the Royal New Zealand Navy]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* McDougall, R J  (1989) ''New Zealand Naval Vessels.'' Page 98-100. Government Printing Office. {{ISBN|978-0-477-01399-4}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hawea}}\n\n{{Mil-ship-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Lake-class patrol vessels]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Lowestoft]]\n", "name_user": "Onco p53", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: Lake Hawea \u2192 Lake H\u0101wea as perWikipedia:Naming_conventions_(New_Zealand)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMNZS_Hawea_(1975)"}
{"title_page": "Asian Men's Volleyball Championship", "text_new": "{{about|the men's indoor volleyball tournament|the men's tournament|Asian Women's Volleyball Championship}}\n{{short description|indoor volleyball competition for men's national teams}}\n{{Infobox sports league\n| logo           = \n| pixels         =\n| sport          = Volleyball\n| founded        = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1975}}\n| inaugural      = [[1975 Asian Men's Volleyball Championship|1975]]\n| teams          = 16 (finals)<br>65 (eligible to enter qualification)\n| continent      = [[Asia]] and [[Oceania]] ([[Asian Volleyball Confederation|AVC]])\n| champion       = {{vb|IRI}} (3rd title) \n| most_champs    = {{vbw|JPN}} (9 titles)\n| TV             = SMMTV\n| website        = {{nowrap|[http://asianvolleyball.net Asian Volleyball Confederation]}}\n| upcoming_season = 2021 Asian Men's Volleyball Championship\n}}\nThe '''Asian Men's Volleyball Championship''' is an international [[volleyball]] competition in [[Asia]] and [[Oceania]] contested by the senior men's national teams of the members of [[Asian Volleyball Confederation]] (AVC), the sport's continent governing body. The initial gap between championships was four years, but since [[1987 Asian Men's Volleyball Championship|1987]] they have been awarded every two years. The current champion is [[Iran men's national volleyball team|Iran]], which won its third title at the [[2019 Asian Men's Volleyball Championship|2019 tournament]].\n\nThe 20 Asian Championship tournaments have been won by five different national teams. [[Japan men's national volleyball team|Japan]] have won nine times. The other Asian Championship winners are [[South Korea men's national volleyball team|South Korea]], with four titles; [[China men's national volleyball team|China]] with three titles; [[Iran men's national volleyball team|Iran]] with three titles; and [[Australia men's national volleyball team|Australia]], with one title.\n\nThe [[2019 Asian Men's Volleyball Championship|2019 Asian Championship]] took place in Tehran, Iran.\n\n==Results summary==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; width: 100%; text-align: center;\"\n|- bgcolor=#c1d8ff\n!rowspan=2 width=6%|Year\n!rowspan=2 width=12%|Host\n!width=1% rowspan=23 bgcolor=ffffff|\n!colspan=3|Final\n!width=1% rowspan=23 bgcolor=ffffff|\n!colspan=3|Third place match\n!width=1% rowspan=25 bgcolor=#ffffff|\n!rowspan=2 width=5%|Teams\n|- bgcolor=#efefef\n!width=14%|Champions\n!width=9%|Score\n!width=14%|Runners-up\n!width=14%|3rd place\n!width=9%|Score\n!width=14%|4th place\n|-\n|1975<br />[[1975 Asian Men's Volleyball Championship|Details]]\n|{{flagicon|AUS}}<br>[[Melbourne]]\n|'''{{vb-big|JPN|1947}}'''\n|[[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]]\n|{{vb-big|KOR|1949}}\n|{{vb-big|CHN}}\n|[[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]]\n|{{vb-big|AUS}}\n|7\n|- bgcolor=#E8E8F0\n|1979<br />[[1979 Asian Men's Volleyball Championship|Details]]\n|{{flagicon|BHR|1972}}<br>[[Manama]]\n|'''{{vb-big|CHN}}'''\n|[[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]]\n|{{vb-big|KOR|1949}}\n|{{vb-big|JPN|1947}}\n|[[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]]\n|{{vb-big|AUS}}\n|15\n|-\n|1983<br />[[1983 Asian Men's Volleyball Championship|Details]]\n|{{flagicon|JPN|1947}}<br>[[Tokyo]]\n|'''{{vb-big|JPN|1947}}'''\n|[[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]]\n|{{vb-big|CHN}}\n|{{vb-big|KOR|1949}}\n|[[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]]\n|{{vb-big|TPE}}\n|11\n|- bgcolor=#E8E8F0\n|1987<br />[[1987 Asian Men's Volleyball Championship|Details]]\n|{{flagicon|KUW}}<br>[[Kuwait City]]\n|'''{{vb-big|JPN|1947}}'''\n|'''3\u20130'''\n|{{vb-big|CHN}}\n|{{vb-big|KOR|1984}}\n|'''3\u20130'''\n|{{vb-big|KUW}}\n|17\n|-\n|1989<br />[[1989 Asian Men's Volleyball Championship|Details]]\n|{{flagicon|KOR|1984}}<br>[[Seoul]]\n|'''{{vb-big|KOR|1984}}'''\n|'''3\u20130'''\n|{{vb-big|JPN|1947}}\n|{{vb-big|CHN}}\n|'''3\u20132'''\n|{{vb-big|PAK}}\n|19\n|- bgcolor=#E8E8F0\n|1991<br />[[1991 Asian Men's Volleyball Championship|Details]]\n|{{flagic